Here’s how to get you what you want (VPN provider / TOR exit / proxy / hosting) reliably, even before you plug in all the API keys — plus a Bolt prompt you can copy with keyboard only.

1) Why you “missed TOR” on that IP

Right now you’re depending on the third-party sources you’ve wired. If none of them flags it as Tor exit (or they’re failing due to missing keys / 401/403), your UI will show “Not detected.”

Fix: add a deterministic Tor exit check that doesn’t rely on paid providers:

Best approach (fast + accurate)

Pull the Tor Project exit list (or Onionoo) on a schedule (daily / every 6h)

Store it in a small table (or even KV/cache)

When an IP lookup happens: check ip in tor_exit_list

This becomes your “ground truth” for Tor exit detection.

2) Your “Privacy & Anonymization” card should be its own mini-engine

For school board triage, the card should output:

TOR Exit: Yes/No (with source = Tor exit list)

VPN: Yes/No + Provider name (Nord/Surfshark/Mullvad/etc.) if you can identify it

Proxy: Yes/No (datacenter proxy vs residential proxy if possible)

Hosting/DC: Yes/No (and show ASN/org)

Residential vs Hosting heuristic: “Likely Hosting”, “Likely Residential”, “Unknown”

How to get VPN provider

Even without “fancy APIs,” you can do a lot:

Provider often appears via org / ASN (e.g., “M247”, “OVH”, “DigitalOcean”, etc.)

If you want true “VPN Brand” detection, that usually needs a provider DB (IPQualityScore / similar) — but you can still start with a strong heuristic.

UI suggestion: show “VPN Provider: Unknown” rather than just “VPN: Not detected” when you lack coverage.

3) Your score shouldn’t go weird when sources fail (401/403)

Your screenshot shows sources erroring (ThreatFox HTTP 401, URLhaus HTTP 401, teoh HTTP 403). That’s expected until keys / headers are correct.

Two important tweaks:

Don’t penalize the threat score for missing sources

Show a small badge like: Source unavailable (API key missing) vs No hits

That keeps the analyst from misreading “clean” when it’s actually “not checked.”

